---
title: Southwestern Pork Burgers with Chipotle Sauce and Breaded Zucchini
description: Think you know burgers? Think again: these patties defy any expectations you might’ve had. For starters, they’re made with pork, which has a light and lean flavor that’s perfect for dressing up with bold, earthy spices inspired by Tex-Mex cuisine. When you add on melty cheddar cheese and a creamy chipotle sauce, things only get better (and then some when you factor in the crispy breaded zucchini on the side).
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/5c3f3eb6c445fa421d1640c8-e12eb45c.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/southwestern-pork-burgers-5c3f3eb6c445fa421d1640c8-a7402fc3.pdf
author: HelloFresh
servings: 2
time required: 35 minutes
cuisine: American
nutrition:
  calories: 990 kcal
  fat: 63 g
  saturated fat: 22 g
  carbohydrates: 63 g
  sugar: 13 g
  protein: 42 g
  sodium: 1080 g
course: main course
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/southwestern-pork-burgers-5c3f3eb6c445fa421d1640c8
---

Wash and dry all produce. Adjust rack to upper position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Line a #baking sheet{} with foil and lightly oil. Trim @zucchini{1}, then slice into ⅓-inch-thick rounds. Slice @beefsteak tomato{1} into thin rounds. On a #plate{}, mix @panko breadcrumbs{1/2}(cup) with a drizzle of @vegetable oil{drizzle}, @Southwest spice blend{1%tsp}, and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

Brush half the @sour cream{3%tbsp} onto one side of each zucchini round. Season with salt and pepper. Working one round at a time, press coated sides of zucchini into panko mixture, pressing to adhere. Arrange on lined baking sheet with coated side facing up. Bake in oven until zucchini is tender and panko is golden brown, ~{20-22%minutes}.

Meanwhile, place @ground pork{10%oz}, half the @garlic powder{1/2%tsp}, and remaining @Southwest spice blend{1%tsp} in a #medium bowl{} (we sent extra spice). Mix to combine. Season with salt and pepper. Using your hands, shape mixture into two patties, each slightly wider than the buns.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{drizzle} in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add patties and cook until almost at desired doneness, ~{4-5%minutes} per side. Top each patty with a slice of @mature cheddar cheese{2%slices}, then cover pan with a #lid{} or aluminum foil. Let cheddar melt, about ~{1%minute}. Meanwhile, split @brioche buns{2} in half and place on another baking sheet. Toast in oven until golden, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Halve @lime{1}. In a #small bowl{}, stir together @mayonnaise{2%tbsp}, a squeeze or two of lime, @chipotle powder{1/4%tsp}, and remaining @sour cream{3%tbsp} and @garlic powder{1/2%tsp}. Season with salt and pepper.

> Give the sauce a taste and add more chipotle or lime if you like (you may not use all—save the rest for another use).

Spread as much chipotle sauce as you like onto cut sides of buns. Fill buns with patties and tomato slices. Serve with zucchini on the side. Use any remaining sauce for dipping.